Indian shares rally on foreign , local fund buying . Shares across Indian bourses rebounded for the second successive day as foreign funds joined local investment institutions on Wednesday in bargain hunting , brokers said . " Fund managers turned bargain hunters as valuations looked attractive , " one broker said referring to the recent slide in blue - chip shares . The 30 - share BSE index jumped 90 . 16 points , or 2 . 72 percent , to 3 , 406 . 22 . The Delhi index rose 21 . 88 points , or 2 . 8 percent , to 795 . 74 . Delhi brokers said expectations that Finance Minister P . Chidambaram might reconsider the 12 . 9 percent minimum tax on companies was one factor that pushed the market . The tax was proposed in last month ' s budget which will be passed by parliament next month . The 500 - stock CRISIL firmed 13 . 82 points , or 2 . 07 percent , to 680 . 27 . The 200 - share midcap index gained 4 . 27 points , or 0 . 91 percent , to 475 . 84 . Bombay traders said the decision on Tuesday by U . S . Federal Reserve to keep interest rates unchanged was a " morale booster . " Some Japanese and Hongkong - based funds were hectic buyers . Foreign funds favoured power and heavy engineering stocks , the traders said . Tata Power firmed 8 . 25 rupees to 153 and BSES 7 . 0 to 187 . 50 while L & T rose 5 . 75 to 247 . 50 . Unit Trust of India , the country ' s biggest investment institution , was a keen buyer , the traders said . TELCO rallied 18 rupees to 483 , Reliance 14 . 75 to 215 . 75 , ACC rose 128 rupees to 2 , 152 . 50 , HDFC 30 . 75 to 2 , 657 . 75 , Asian Paints 11 . 75 to 365 . 75 , Grasim 13 . 25 to 429 . 25 , SBI 6 . 75 to 273 , TISCO 9 . 25 to 193 , ICICI 6 . 75 to 76 . 50 and ITC 5 . 50 to 291 . 50 . The Calcutta index gained 8 . 83 points to 450 . 36 and the Madras index 41 . 53 to 3 , 570 . 44 . - - RANJIT GANGADHARAN , Bombay Newsroom + 91 - 22 - 265 - 9000 
